        "passage": "Paragraph 1:\nI think we should never doubt that even as an individual person, we can make a difference to the environment. Trying to protect the environment seems like a huge, impossible challenge and the efforts of governments make it not always successful. But I think it's important for everyone to think about what they can do, because even small actions can have a big effect.\n\nParagraph 2:\nI started thinking about my own situation where I live in the countryside. My garden backs onto some hills and fields. Over the years, all the trees have been removed from there. The result was that when it rained, our garden became covered in water and soil, because there were no tree roots to stop the soil being washed down the hill. I didn't mind the water - that soon disappeared - but the soil covered and damaged my plants. Many didn't survive. At the same time, I was sorry to see the hill without the trees it used to have. I became very worried about the impact on the future.\n\nParagraph 3:\nThen I read an online article about a project in Kenya, where the villagers grew and planted trees to help the land recover. I decided to organise my neighbours to plant small trees on the hill above our houses. Initially, we did have problems because we didn't have the money to buy the small trees we wanted to plant. Then we tried to get some shop owners in the town involved because they agreed the trees might make the area more attractive to visitors. Finally, one cafe owner agreed to give us the cash we needed.\n\nParagraph 4:\nSince then, the trees we bought have really grown, so now we don't get flooding any more. Once our little forest was established, we decided to keep bees. A friend in my village is an expert. He taught us all how to do it and now we even produce our own honey. Who knows? Maybe other groups of people will follow our example. You see, everyone can do something to make a difference.",
