    "scriptFull": "Preliminary English Test - Listening Test 2\nAudio Script\n\nPart 1\nThere are four parts to the test. You will hear each part twice. For each part of the test, there will be time for you to look through the questions and time for you to check your answers. Write your answers on the question paper. You will have six minutes at the end of the test to copy your answers onto the answer sheet.\nThe recording will now be stopped. Please ask any questions now because you must not speak during the test.\nNow open your question paper and look at part 1.\nNow we are ready to start. For each question, choose the correct answer.\nQuestion 1: What will the woman bring on the camping trip?\nMan: The weather looks good for our camping trip at the weekend.\nWoman: Yeah. I won't have to pack a blanket if it's not going to be cold. A light sleeping bag will be fine.\nMan: Yeah. Now, I know you've got a really powerful torch. Could you bring it, because it still gets dark fairly early on?\nWoman: I'll make a note so I won't forget. Don't worry. And I've made a note to remind me to bring plenty of rope.\nMan: Absolutely. It's always useful.\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\nQuestion 2: What is the woman's new hobby?\nMan: How are you? I haven't seen you for ages. You haven't been at the cycling club for a couple of months now.\nWoman: No, but I'm absolutely fine, thanks. I've been really busy at work and finishing later than usual. I've been trying to keep fit though by doing some dancing. My sister's been teaching me.\nMan: What a good idea! I read somewhere that it's better for you than sports like swimming or jogging.\nWoman: Well, when the weather gets cooler I'll probably start jogging too.\nMan: I'll come with you.\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\nQuestion 3: Which film will they go and see?\nMan: Do you fancy going to the cinema this evening?\nWoman: I'd love to. I've got to get up really early tomorrow. But if it finishes before, say, 9.15, that'd be great.\nMan: Well, there are a couple of possibilities. I know you really like horror films and there's one which finishes at 7.45. The next one ends at half past eight, but that's a comedy and I'm not sure you'd like it.\nWoman: Actually, tonight I do fancy watching something bit lighter. So shall we go for that?\nMan: That suits me.\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\nQuestion 4: What present does the girl decide to buy?\nAssistant: Can I help you?\nGirl: Yes, thanks. I don't have much time. I'm looking for a gift for my mum's birthday and your sale prices are really good. She loves gold but I can only see silver necklaces.\nAssistant: I'm afraid those are the only ones in the sale but these gold rings and bracelets have a good discount on them.\nGirl: Oh! I didn't see those. They're lovely, especially the bracelets. Mum doesn't wear rings. This one will be perfect. I'll take that please.\nAssistant: OK.\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\nQuestion 5: Where will the friends go today?\nWoman: I wish I'd checked the tourist information website before we came.\nMan: Yes, we'll have to come back on a day when the Natural History Museum's open. It's such a shame we'll miss that today.\nWoman: I agree. I love the dinosaurs, but the art museum's open and there's an interesting show on there. And of course I'm happy to see the Science Museum again.\nMan: Yeah, I know you really enjoyed the space exhibition last year, but I'd prefer to see paintings if you don't mind.\nWoman: Of course not.\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\nQuestion 6: What is the woman's advice for the man? (How to get to the pharmacy)\nMan: Can you tell me how to get to the nearest pharmacy?\nWoman: It's quite a long walk. You go along this road, past the railway station and then over the bridge.\nMan: Yes.\nWoman: You soon come to a crossroads and turn right. You'll see the big post office opposite you. You go past that and the pharmacy is near it, on the same side of the road.\nMan: I think I know it. Is it near a roundabout?\nWoman: That's it. But remember, if you see the playground, you've gone too far.\nMan: Thanks.\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\nQuestion 7: Which area of the sports centre is closed today?\nSpeaker: This is a recorded message for the Hillside Sports Centre. Opening hours are 6am to 11pm. In order to do essential repairs we're closing different areas of the centre for short periods of time. The gym repairs are now complete and it is open as usual. But the swimming pool won't be ready to open again until Monday 24th August. Squash court repairs will not take place until September so they can be booked as normal.\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\nThat is the end of part one.\n\nPart 2\nNow turn to part 2, questions 8 to 13. For each question, choose the correct answer.\nQuestion 8: You will hear two friends talking about a group holiday they are both going on.\nMan: Hi, have you finished your packing?\nWoman: Almost. Don't worry, I won't forget the sun cream like last time.\nMan: Good. I'm bringing some anyway. I just wanted to say, you know the coach is leaving at a quarter to seven?\nWoman: Thanks, I do. They told us that right at the beginning, though I didn't really know why we have to set off so early.\nMan: Well, there is a lot of traffic because of roadworks. And we don't want to miss the plane.\nWoman: Oh, right. That's good then.\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\nQuestion 9: You will hear two colleagues talking about this weekend.\nWoman: Are you going anywhere this weekend?\nMan: I haven't decided yet. Me and my husband had a lovely time at the beach last weekend. It was a beautiful place, though it rained quite a lot so we couldn't always see the wonderful views. But we met a lovely couple and we all got on really well.\nWoman: That kind of thing makes it so much more fun, doesn't it?\nMan: Exactly. It's who you're with that matters. It's not all about where you go or whether the sun is shining.\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\nQuestion 10: You will hear two friends talking about recycling at their college.\nGirl: Do you have lots of recycling bins near your classroom?\nBoy: Of course, though not many of the students use them, I'm afraid. We've got three different bins in a great place, just outside the room. They've got clear labels on them, but I've noticed that almost all my classmates don't bother to read them.\nGirl: So they don't recycle?\nBoy: That's not it. They put things in the wrong place. Use the food bin for plastic and stuff like that. It really annoys me.\nGirl: I can imagine. I wonder if there's anything we can do.\nBoy: I don't think so.\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\nQuestion 11: You will hear two friends talking about a concert they are going to see.\nMan: Are you looking forward to the concert tonight?\nWoman: Of course. I haven't been to one for ages. The last one we saw was brilliant. Do you remember? We were on the back row, but we could see everything as if we were in the front seats.\nMan: Yeah, let's hope tonight's will be as good. It's quite a large orchestra, with musicians from all over the world. And I'll be interested to hear how they play together for the first time. They put together quite an unusual selection in the programme, which I didn't expect.\nWoman: Yeah, great!\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\nQuestion 12: You will hear two friends talking about a gym class they both went to.\nWoman: What did you think of our exercise class?\nMan: Tiring, but I did enjoy all the different movements we did, and the instructor was really encouraging. I wasn't always sure what he wanted us to do, but I looked at everyone else and followed what they did. But it was much better than the one I used to go to. The teacher really pushed us too hard there.\nWoman: I remember you saying he got you to use all those weights to make you work harder.\nMan: They were useful, but it was a bit miserable. Well, you must be glad you changed.\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\nQuestion 13: You will hear a girl talking to her brother about his back problems.\nGirl: Dad said you hurt your back.\nBoy: Yeah, I'm not sure how I did it. Perhaps when I played badminton last week. Don't worry, I won't be playing for a while.\nGirl: That's about the only exercise you're getting at the moment, so don't think of giving it up. Maybe you could talk to one of the instructors at the club. He could give you some ideas about how to avoid problems.\nBoy: Maybe.\nGirl: And when you're at home working at the computer, you're probably spending too much time sitting in a bad position.\nBoy: Yes, I need to remember not to do that.\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\nAnd that is the end of part two.\n\nPart 3\nNow turn to part 3. 14 to 19. For each question, write the correct answer in the gap. Write one or two words or a number or a date or a time.\nYou will hear a tennis club leader called Sam giving a presentation about the changes that have been made to the clubhouse.\nSam: Evening everyone. As you know, we've been closed for the last two months, but I'm now happy to welcome you to our new look building and to tell you about the changes we've made. The main thing was to stop water coming in through the section of roof over the showers. During storms, rain was pouring in and damaging the room next door, the cafeteria. Everything's a lot drier now.\nWe've also been doing a lot of decorating. We've painted the walls of the reception area in a deep blue and the doors red. The changing rooms used to be a boring grey. We've painted them yellow, which looks much more cheerful. We always want your ideas for how to improve our club, so we've placed the comments box in a better position. It used to be outside the club office, but now we've put it beside the lift so everyone can find it more easily. Please do feel free to write suggestions and put them in the box.\nWe're pleased to announce a new exhibition in the hall. During the work on the building, we found some old tennis kit in the cupboards. It's the kind of thing you see people wearing in black and white photos, so we decided to put it all in a display. We hope you find it interesting. We've also added to the members' kitchen. As you know, we've had a kettle and a small coffee machine for some time, but we've put in a microwave for those who want to heat their own food.\nFinally, we've made a change to the car park. We've made spaces for people who are bringing their children. These are next to the spaces that were already there for members using wheelchairs, a few metres from the entrance.\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\n\nPart 4\nNow turn to part 4, questions 20 to 25. For each question, choose the correct answer. You will hear an interview with a girl called Polly who recently travelled around England with friends.\nInterviewer: Our guest today is Polly Bell, who's just travelled around England with three friends. You did a lot of the journey by train, Polly. Why was that?\nPolly: Well, I toured Europe quite a bit with my family when I was younger, by car, and what I remember was how quickly we travelled and how little we saw of each city. Not very exciting. On the train we had plenty of time to look out of the window at the changing landscapes, which was the nicest thing. We didn't get to talk to as many other passengers as we'd hoped though.\nInterviewer: And did you have any worries before you started your journey?\nPolly: Well, my friends talked a lot about the most important tourist sites in each part of the country and were stressed about not missing anything. I don't like to decide what to see until we get there. So I didn't agree with them. It's not a problem. They know we all have different opinions. But what bothered me was deciding how much we should spend each day, making sure we could afford everything we needed for the whole time.\nInterviewer: You stayed on a boat for a while. Was that fun?\nPolly: Yeah, for three days. It was great. I already knew about the background to canals and about the animals and plants that live on the water. What was most amazing was the challenge of working out how to cook, sleep and so on with limited room. We were very proud of ourselves for doing it so well.\nInterviewer: Did you go to any art galleries or museums?\nPolly: Only one, a football museum in Manchester. It was full of football fans, which is what you'd expect. But even though I know absolutely nothing about sport, I really liked it because all the exhibitions were so well designed and clear.\nInterviewer: What advice would you give to people doing a similar journey to the one you've done?\nPolly: Don't carry too much. A light backpack is much better than a big suitcase. And whatever the time of year, carry an umbrella rather than heavy coats or sweaters. It's more likely to rain than be cold. Take a chess set or cards with you to keep you and your friends busy on long journeys.\nInterviewer: Would you go on a similar tour again?\nPolly: Definitely. Train journeys aren't always relaxing and timetables don't always work out as planned, but the most wonderful holidays are ones where you have variety in what you do, where you're not doing the same thing every day.\nNow listen again. [Repeat]\nThat is the end of the test.",
